    "breadcrumb": "Home",
    "content": "Personal Feedback ‚Äì AWS First Cloud Journey (FCJ) During my time in AWS Vietnam under the First Cloud Journey (FCJ) program, I experienced a learning environment that challenged me, accelerated my growth, and pushed me beyond the typical student-level knowledge.\nFCJ rewards those who are self-driven. I believe it is an exceptional program, but not universally easy. It benefits students who come with curiosity, resilience, and the willingness to learn through action rather than instruction. People like me, who enjoy exploring deeply and independently, will grow extremely fast here.\nOverall Evaluation What FCJ Did Extremely Well Strength Why it matters Autonomy to learn \u0026 build independently I wasn‚Äôt handed answers, I learned by thinking, trying, and solving. Full real AWS access (not sandbox-level) Allowed true production-oriented experimentation, not just theory. Cloud Optimization \u0026 Cost Awareness Rarely taught in school, yet critical in real cloud engineering. Hands-off mentoring approach Guided by questions and direction, not micromanagement. Strong documentation \u0026 learning resources Helped me research deeply and build at my own pace. Growth in Backend + DevOps + Security Redis caching, IAM, KMS, CloudWatch, CI/CD, and more, all hands-on, not just lectures. High learning curve, in a good way The pace never felt boring. You learn as fast as you push yourself. The program shaped my mindset as much as my technical skills, I now think in terms of scalability, cost, security, monitoring, failure-tolerance, not just ‚Äúmake it run‚Äù.\nWhere FCJ Can Improve FCJ teaches the tools, but could add more production practice Technical knowledge was excellent, AWS services, backend development, optimization principles, but I believe the program could be even better with more exposure to real production workflows, such as:\nImprovement Suggestion Benefit to Future Interns More production-style simulations Helps interns learn how systems behave under real load. Practical troubleshooting challenges Builds confidence in debugging failures \u0026 analyzing incidents. More real-world scenario workshops Connects AWS theory with actual industry operations. Not a criticism, more like potential fuel to make an already strong program even stronger.\nWho I Recommend FCJ To I would absolutely recommend FCJ, but only to the right type of person.\nPerfect for:\nStudents who want to build, not just watch People who enjoy self-learning \u0026 documentation digging Those who like challenge over comfort Anyone who wants real AWS, not just classroom AWS Not ideal for:\nSomeone who waits for instructions Someone afraid to try, break, learn, retry Someone looking for 9-5 low effort routine FCJ is not easy. But it is worth it, massively.\nFinal Thoughts FCJ has been one of the most valuable learning experiences I‚Äôve ever had.\nI walk away not only with technical skills, but with mindset, discipline, and confidence that I can build, scale, secure, and optimize cloud systems on my own.\nMy conclusion is simple:\nFCJ doesn‚Äôt just teach cloud, it shapes cloud engineers.",
